definition.value: a laryngeal inflammation AE that has moderate sore throat; analgesics indicated
a laryngeal inflammation AE that has severe throat pain; endoscopic intervention indicated
a laryngeal mucositis AE that has endoscopic findings only; mild discomfort with normal intake
a laryngeal mucositis AE that has moderate discomfort; altered oral intake
a laryngeal mucositis AE that has severe pain; severely altered eating/swallowing; medical intervention indicated
a laryngeal mucositis AE that has life-threatening airway compromise; urgent intervention indicated (e.g., tracheotomy or intubation)
a laryngeal obstruction AE that has symptomatic (e.g., noisy airway breathing), but causing no respiratory distress; medical management indicated (e.g., steroids); limiting instrumental ADL
a laryngeal obstruction AE that has limiting self care ADL; stridor; endoscopic intervention indicated (e.g., stent, laser)
a laryngeal stenosis AE that has symptomatic (e.g., noisy airway breathing), but causing no respiratory distress; medical management indicated (e.g., steroids)
a laryngeal stenosis AE that has limiting self care ADL; stridor; endoscopic intervention indicated (e.g., stent, laser)
a laryngopharyngeal dysesthesia AE that has moderate symptoms; mild anxiety, but no dyspnea; short duration of observation and or anxiolytic indicated; limiting instrumental ADL
a laryngopharyngeal dysesthesia AE that has severe symptoms; dyspnea and swallowing difficulty; limiting self care ADL
a laryngospasm AE that has transient episode; intervention not indicated
a laryngospasm AE that has recurrent episodes; noninvasive intervention indicated (e.g., breathing technique, pressure point massage)
a laryngospasm AE that has persistent or severe episodes associated with syncope; urgent intervention indicated (e.g., fiberoptic laryngoscopy, intubation, botox injection)
a pharyngeal fistula AE that has symptomatic; tube thoracostomy or medical intervention indicated; limiting instrumental ADL
a pharyngeal fistula AE that has severe symptoms; limiting self care ADL; endoscopic or operative intervention indicated (e.g., stent or primary closure)
a pharyngeal mucositis AE that has endoscopic findings only; minimal symptoms with normal oral intake; mild pain but analgesics not indicated
a pharyngeal mucositis AE that has moderate pain and analgesics indicated; altered oral intake; limiting instrumental ADL
a pharyngeal mucositis AE that has severe pain; unable to adequately aliment or hydrate orally; limiting self care ADL
a pharyngeal necrosis AE that has inability to aliment adequately by GI tract; tube feeding or TPN indicated; radiologic, endoscopic, or operative intervention indicated
a pharyngeal stenosis AE that has symptomatic (e.g., noisy airway breathing), but causing no respiratory distress; medical management indicated (e.g., steroids); limiting instrumental ADL
a pharyngeal stenosis AE that has limiting self care ADL; stridor; endoscopic intervention indicated (e.g., stent, laser)
a pharyngeal stenosis AE that has life-threatening airway compromise; urgent intervention indicated (e.g., tracheotomy or intubation)
a pulmonary fistula AE that has symptomatic; tube thoracostomy or medical management indicated; limiting instrumental ADL
a pulmonary fistula AE that has limiting self care ADL; endoscopic stenting or operative intervention indicated
a retinoic acid syndrome AE that has fluid retention; <3 kg of weight gain; intervention with fluid restriction and/or diuretics indicated
a tracheal fistula AE that has symptomatic; tube thoracostomy or medical intervention indicated; limiting instrumental ADL
a tracheal fistula AE that has severe symptoms; limiting self care ADL; endoscopic or operative intervention indicated (e.g., stent or primary closure)
a tracheal fistula AE that has life-threatening consequences; urgent operative intervention indicated (e.g., thoracoplasty, chronic open drainage or multiple thoracotomies)
a tracheal mucositis AE that has endoscopic findings only; minimal hemoptysis, pain, or respiratory symptoms
a tracheal mucositis AE that has severe pain; hemorrhage or respiratory symptoms; limiting self care ADL
a tracheal stenosis AE that has symptomatic (e.g., noisy airway breathing), but causing no respiratory distress; medical management indicated (e.g., steroids)
a tracheal stenosis AE that has stridor or respiratory distress limiting self care ADL; endoscopic intervention indicated (e.g., stent, laser)
a tracheal stenosis AE that has life-threatening airway compromise; urgent intervention indicated (e.g., tracheotomy or intubation)
an azoospermia AE that has absence of sperm in ejaculate
A breast atrophy AE that has asymmetry >1/3 of breast volume; severe atrophy
an ejaculation disorder AE that has diminished ejaculation
an ejaculation disorder AE that has anejaculation or retrograde ejaculation
a genital edema AE that has mild swelling or obscuration of anatomic architecture on close inspection
a genital edema AE that has readily apparent obscuration of anatomic architecture; obliteration of skin folds; readily apparent deviation from normal anatomic contour
a genital edema AE that has lymphorrhea; gross deviation from normal anatomic contour; limiting self care ADL
a gynecomastia AE that has asymptomatic breast enlargement
a gynecomastia AE that has symptomatic (e.g., pain or psychosocial impact)
a hematosalpinx AE that has minimal bleeding identified on imaging study or laparoscopy; intervention not indicated
an irregular menstruation AE that has intermittent menses with skipped menses for no more than 1 to 3 months
an irregular menstruation AE that has intermittent menses with skipped menses for more than 4 to 6 months
an irregular menstruation AE that has persistent amenorrhea for more than 6 months
a lactation disorder AE that has mild changes in lactation, not significantly affecting production or expression of breast milk
a lactation disorder AE that has changes in lactation, significantly affecting breast production or expression of breast milk
